04592nam a22005295i 9780889207264DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061994xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892072647 a10.51644/97808892072642doi  a(DE-B1597)667476  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBM501b.L57 1994eb 7aREL1140002bisacsh04a296.1/25061 aLightstone, Jack N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Rhetoric of the Babylonian Talmud, Its Social Meaning and Context /cJack N. Lightstone. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (331 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Christianity and Judaism ;v600tFront Matter -- tContents -- tCharts -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations and Editions -- tIntroduction -- tBavli’s Structural Formularies -- tBavli’s Structural Formularies in Comparative Relief -- tBavli’s Dialectical Formularies -- tBavli’s Dialectical Formularies in Comparative Relief -- tSummary and Conclusions: The Social Meaning and Context of Bavli’s Rhetoric -- tA Comparative Analysis of the Distribution of Selected Structural Formulae in Nine Tractates of the Bavli -- tThe Hebrew-Aramaic Texts of b. Avodah Zarah 14b-16a and b. Bekorot 2a-5b -- tReferences and Selected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tSR Supplements0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVirtually from its redaction about the sixth century A.D., the Babylonian Talmud became the rabbinic document par excellence. Through its lens almost all previous canonical rabbinic tradition was refracted. Study and mastery of the Talmud marked one as a rabbi, a “master.” This book examines the character, use and social meaning of the formalized rhetoric which pervades the Babylonian Talmud. It explores, first, how the editors of the Talmud employ a consistent and highly laconic code of formalized linguistic terms and literary patterns to create the Talmud’s (renowned) dialectical, analytic “essays.” Second, the work considers the social meanings implicitly communicated by the use of this rhetoric, which not only provided an authoritative model for modes of thought and for treatment of earlier authoritative Judaic tradition, but also reflected, reinforced or helped engender new social definitions. Through comparison of the Talmud’s rhetoric with that of other, earlier rabbinic documents and by placing the editing of the Talmud against the backdrop of the social and political situation of Rabbinism in the Late Persian Empire, the book relates the Talmud’s creation and promulgation to a major shift in Rabbinism’s understanding of the social role, “rabbi,” and to the emergence and ascendancy of the talmudic academy (the Yeshiva) as the primary institution of Rabbinism toward the end of Late Antiquity. In its agenda, and methodological and theoretical perspectives, The Rhetoric of the Babylonian Talmud brings together the insights and tools of historical, literary and rhetorical analysis of the New Testament and of early rabbinic literature, on the one hand, and the sociological and anthropological study of religion, on the other.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRabbinical literature. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920726440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207264423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207264/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade e